        <div id="content">
          <h1 class="title" id="page-title">Beware…Tax Bite is Coming!</h1>                                        <div id="node-423" class="node clear-block">



  <div class="meta">
    </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-type-nodereference field-field-viewpoint-bios">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                    <a href="/alan-ekstein">Alan Ekstein, CPA </a>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<div class="field field-type-filefield field-field-viewpoint-file">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                    <p id="mp3player_1" class="mp3player" data="soundFile=http://www.bonadio.com/sites/default/files/viewpoint_file/tax_bitefinal.mp3">You may need: <a href='http://get.adobe.com/flashplayer/'>Adobe Flash Player</a>.</p>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<div class="field field-type-phptext field-field-viewpoint-promo">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                    <h3>Help your colleagues, customers, or friends be well-informed.</h3>
<p><span class="st_twitter_large" displayText="Tweet"></span>
<span class="st_facebook_large" displayText="Facebook"></span>
<span class="st_ybuzz_large" displayText="Yahoo! Buzz"></span>
<span class="st_gbuzz_large" displayText="Google Buzz"></span>
<span class="st_delicious_large" displayText="delicious"></span>
<span class="st_digg_large" displayText="digg"></span>
<span class="st_linkedin_large" displayText="LinkedIn"></span>
<span class="st_newsvine_large" displayText="newsvine"></span>
<span class="st_reddit_large" displayText="reddit"></span>
<span class="st_stumbleupon_large" displayText="StumbleUpon"></span>
<span class="st_email_large" displayText="Email"></span>
<span class="st_sharethis_large" displayText="ShareThis"></span></p>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<div class="field field-type-text field-field-viewpoint-body">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                    <p>What will happen if the federal income tax reductions put into affect in 2001 by President Bush were allowed to sunset after 2010? The answer is simple; every taxpayer will pay higher federal taxes! How much higher depends on your particular situation, but a few simple examples can illustrate the magnitude of the increase. (The examples are taken from our tax research provider CCH, a Walters Kluwer Business):</p>
<ol>
<li>A couple with two children eligible for the child tax credit, filing a joint return and taking the standard deduction, with $130K wage income, $10K in net capital gains and $2K in dividend income. Their tax with no sunset is $19,513 and with the sunset it is $26,343, an increase of $6,830.</li>
<li>A couple, no children, filing a joint return and taking the standard deduction, with $300K in wage income, $50K in net capital gains and $5K in dividend income. Their tax with no sunset is $78,860 and with the sunset it is $91,789, an increase of $12,929.</li>
<li>Single taxpayer with no children, taking the standard deduction, with $70K wage income, $5K net capital gains and $1K dividend income. The tax with no sunset is $12,244 and with the sunset it is $13,842.</li>
</ol>
<p>Here’s a list of items that will drive tax increases if the federal government lets the current law sunset:</p>
<ul>
<li>the reversal of the 2001 tax rate reductions, </li>
<li>the elimination of the 15% maximum tax on qualified dividends, </li>
<li>the increase in the capital gains rate to 20%, </li>
<li>the elimination of the 10% tax bracket, </li>
<li>the reintroduction of the marriage penalty for married taxpayers filing joint returns, </li>
<li>the reintroduction of the itemized deduction phase-out for higher income taxpayers, </li>
<li>the reintroduction of the personal exemption phase-out for higher income taxpayers, </li>
<li>reductions in the Earned Income Credit, </li>
<li>50% reduction in the Child Tax Credit and lowered phase-out income levels, </li>
<li>25% reduction in the Dependent Care Credit, and other similar changes</li>
</ul>
<p>And last but not least, the Alternative Minimum Tax exemption will be lowered to $45,000 for married taxpayers (with similar reductions for other statuses), ensnaring many previously sheltered taxpayers in its clutches.<br /><br />These and many other minor, and not so minor changes, will conspire to substantially increase you taxes in 2011.<br /><br />What can you do to make the tax bite less painful?&nbsp; Here are some suggestions:<br />Project your income and deductions for 2010 and also for 2011. If you have capital gain property that you will need to sell, do it in 2010 not 2011. If you can itemize deductions in some years, but not every year, time your deductions for 2011 and use the standard deduction in 2010. If your adjusted gross income in 2011 is going to be in excess of $70,000 and you itemize your deductions, be very aware of Alternative Minimum Tax (AMT), as it will ensnare the unwary. And finally, keep in close touch with your tax advisor because Congress has a habit of making major tax changes at the end of the year. Sometimes, even in the early part of the following year!<br /><br />If you have any tax questions or seek advisement on your next steps, give us a call at 1-888-353-9313.</p>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
  </div>

  
  
